summary: what were your exact issues with sansa's s5 storyline? like I hated it but ultimately it did end with her getting her home back...
question: what were your exact issues with sansa's s5 storyline? like I hated it but ultimately it did end with her getting her home back and becoming Sansa Stark of winterfell again
answer:
Well the most obvious answer is that it wasn’t her storyline it was Theon’s and Jeyne’s (a character that wasn’t important enough to be included in the show but her rape was apparently too important to be left out) but for me it goes much deeper than that.

By the end of season of season four she has escaped kings landing and is in the vale under a new identity, she is shown as being stronger than she was at the start and capable of playing the game alongside the likes of petyr baelish. Her  experiences in Kingslanding taught her a lot and now she finally gets to be in control. 

Fast forward to season five and baelish takes her to winterfell and convinces her to marry Ramsay to get winterfell back. Early on she has a few “empowering” moments. She gets to see theon again and call him out for “killing” bran and rickon. The first time she’s got to openly express anger towards someone for harming her family. Of course we, the audience, know that theon never killed bran and rickon and unlike Sansa we know how badly theon has been tortured since so Sansa ends up coming off as pretty cruel and uncaring in this scene. Then there is the famous quote “I am Sansa Stark of winterfell, this is my home and you can’t frighten me” which is empowering out of context. It’s the first time she’s been allowed to say something so liberating and empowering that reinforces the fact that she IS Sansa Stark, lady of winterfell not Jeffrey’s betrothed or tyrion’s wife or a prisoner of kingslanding. Then later on in the same episode she is forced into another marriage and brutally raped in the home she just felt like she had reclaimed because as the haters would say silly Sansa Stark thought she could just easily take back her home and her identity and finally be in control and now she’s being taught the worlds worst lesson because the abuse she suffered in kingslanding wasn’t enough to keep her in her place.

It doesn’t matter how empowered she becomes after season five because they gave her back her voice and her agency just to have it taken away again and have her violated in the worst way possible for daring to try and become empowered and take back her home.

summary: I think the problem with Sansa is that when she told tyrion about Jon it was like telling cersei about ned planning to leave...
question: I think the problem with Sansa is that when she told tyrion about Jon it was like telling cersei about ned planning to leave kings landing. she put them in danger for her own personal gain?
answer:
first of all, I wouldn’t say “she put them in danger for her own personal gain” because she was a naive 11 year old child book one (I’m pretty sure this only happened because I don’t remember this actual scene but I may be wrong?) who had no idea what would happen if she told cersei since ned never told her they were in danger and she genuinely thought cersei was a trustworthy mother figure. Second of all, she told Tyrion because she wanted to protect her Family and she thought this was the ONLY way to stop history from repeating itself. She knew what she was doing the second time, she was playing the game but she wasn’t doing it for power or purely for personal gain.

The one thing these scenes do have in common is that Sansa feels like she is in a safe place and actually has the agency to speak up and use her voice without the constant fear that she’d be punished or killed. 

The people who hate her hate that she’s no longer a victim who has no voice and only exists to benefit the other characters and their storylines while quietly surviving. They hate that she wasn't “punished” by the narrative this time. These are the same people who victim blamed her for what happened in kings landing, who defended the season five storyline because it was something that she HAD to go through because it was too soon for her to regain her agency at that point (although some of you didn’t want her regain agency and independence at all and it shows)
